FT  27 NOV 93 / Iraq backs down in UN clash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS, UN Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Iraq last night conceded UN Security Council demands for long-term
monitoring to guard against any revival of its capability to produce weapons
of mass destruction.
The decision means that Baghdad has dropped its insistence that verification
would constitute an unwarranted intrusion and an offence against the
nation's sovereignty. In a letter to the council, Mr Mohamed Said al-Sahaf,
the foreign minister, argued that 'this positive step' and other 'positive
developments' justified the lifting of sanctions, including the embargo on
oil sales.
Mr Rolf Ekeus, head of the UN commission overseeing the elimination of Iraqi
weapons, said the Iraqi move was a major breakthrough.
